];

const shareImage = new URL('/raised-bed-soil-calculator-fill-example.svg', Astro.site).href;

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'How much soil do I need to fill a raised bed?',
    a: 'Multiply length × width × depth (in feet) to get cubic feet. A standard 4×8 bed at 10 inches deep needs about 26.7 cubic feet — roughly 1 cubic yard. Most raised beds need 8–12 inches of soil to give roots room to grow without hitting native soil.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How many bags of soil do I need for a 4×4 raised bed?',
    a: 'A 4×4 bed filled 10 inches deep needs about 13.3 cubic feet. That is roughly 9 bags of 1.5 cu ft soil or 7 bags of 2 cu ft soil. The calculator above auto-fills the 4×4 preset and shows both bag counts live as you adjust the depth.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How many cubic feet is 40 lbs of soil?',
    a: 'A standard 40 lb bag of potting or garden soil holds about 0.75 cubic feet. That means 1 cubic foot weighs roughly 53 lbs, and 1 cubic yard (27 cu ft) weighs about 1,440 lbs. These are averages — actual weight varies by moisture content and soil mix.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How much compost should I mix into raised bed soil?',
    a: 'The classic raised bed mix is 60% topsoil, 30% compost, and 10% perlite or coarse sand for drainage. At minimum, work in 25–30% compost so the bed retains moisture and feeds plants without compacting. Straight garden soil alone compacts too hard for raised beds.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I use potting mix instead of topsoil in a raised bed?',
    a: 'Not on its own — potting mix costs several times more per cubic foot than a topsoil-based blend, and its light, fast-draining structure dries out faster than most raised bed crops want. It works better as one ingredient in a blend than as a full replacement: mixing some potting mix into a topsoil-and-compost base can improve aeration in heavy soil, but filling an entire bed with it gets expensive fast and needs more frequent watering to compensate for the drainage.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How many plants can I fit in my raised bed?',
    a: 'It depends on the crop. In a 4×8 bed using square-foot spacing: 1 tomato or pepper per square foot, 4 lettuce heads, 9 spinach plants, or 16 radishes. Use our Plant Spacing Calculator for a precise grid count with any spacing and bed size.',
  },
];

// FAQBlock component handles FAQPage schema injection automatically.

