---

<CalculatorLayout calculator={calculator} cluster={cluster} intro={intro} lastUpdated={lastUpdated} authorName={authorName} authorUrl={authorUrl} shareImage={shareImage}>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(howToJsonLd)} slot="head" />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbJsonLd)} slot="head" />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(personJsonLd)} slot="head" />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(softwareAppJsonLd)} slot="head" />

  <!-- Desktop sticky TOC in the right sidebar column -->
  <TableOfContents items={tocItems} variant="sidebar" slot="sidebar" />

  <!-- Calculator tool — immediately after intro -->
  <RaisedBedSoilCalculator client:load />

  <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-bark-500">
    Filling pots or containers instead? Use our <a href="/calculators/soil-volume-calculator/" class="text-moss-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-moss-900">Soil Volume Calculator</a>.
  </p>

  <!-- Mobile TOC accordion — below the calculator, collapsed by default, hidden on desktop -->
  <TableOfContents items={tocItems} variant="accordion" />

  <article class="prose prose-bark mt-8 max-w-none prose-headings:font-display prose-headings:text-bark-900 prose-h2:mt-12 prose-h2:scroll-mt-24 prose-h2:text-2xl prose-h2:font-semibold prose-h3:text-lg prose-h3:font-semibold prose-a:text-moss-700 prose-strong:text-bark-900">

    <h2 id="how-much-soil-do-i-need">How Much Soil Do I Need for a Raised Bed?</h2>

    <p>
      The answer depends on three numbers: your bed&rsquo;s <strong>length</strong>, <strong>width</strong>, and how deep you want to fill it. Most raised beds do best at <strong>8&ndash;12 inches</strong> of soil depth. That gives vegetable roots room to spread without hitting compacted native soil underneath. Shallow beds (under 6 inches) restrict root growth for most crops; go at least 10&ndash;12 inches for tomatoes, peppers, and root vegetables.
    </p>

    <figure class="my-6 float-right ml-6 w-48 sm:w-64">
      <img
        src="/raised-bed-soil-calculator-fill-example.svg"
        alt="Soil being added to a raised garden bed, showing fill depth"
        width="400"
        height="300"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-xl border border-moss-100 bg-moss-50/30"
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-2 text-xs text-bark-500">
        Fill to within 1&ndash;2 inches of the rim to allow for settling.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Once you have the volume in <strong>cubic feet</strong>, divide by 27 to get <strong>cubic yards</strong> — the unit bulk suppliers quote in. For bagged soil, divide by the bag size (typically 1.5 or 2 cubic feet) and round up to the nearest whole bag.
    </p>

    <p>
      Don&rsquo;t fill with straight topsoil or garden soil pulled from the ground. It compacts in a raised bed, drains poorly, and stunts plant growth. The standard raised bed <strong>soil mix ratio</strong> is <strong>60% topsoil, 30% <a href="/calculators/compost-calculator/">compost</a>, and 10% perlite or coarse sand</strong>. This blend holds moisture, drains excess water, and provides the organic matter vegetables need. If you&rsquo;re buying a pre-mixed &ldquo;raised bed mix&rdquo; in bags, it usually approximates this ratio &mdash; check the label. Use our <a href="/calculators/compost-calculator/">Compost Calculator</a> to figure out exactly how much you&rsquo;ll need.
    </p>

    <p>
      This 60/30/10 split isn&rsquo;t the only reputable formula out there, and we don&rsquo;t present it as the one correct answer. A <strong>50/30/20 blend</strong> (soil, compost, and a larger 20% aeration component like perlite or coarse sand) is a common alternative for heavier native soils that need more drainage help. Square Foot Gardening&rsquo;s well-known <strong>&ldquo;Mel&rsquo;s Mix&rdquo;</strong> skips topsoil entirely in favor of equal thirds compost, peat moss or coco coir, and vermiculite. Which one works best depends on your goals &mdash; 60/30/10 is a solid, economical default for most in-ground-adjacent raised beds, but if you&rsquo;re optimizing for maximum moisture retention or working from a true no-topsoil system, one of these alternatives may suit you better.
    </p>

    <p>
      For large beds (more than 2&ndash;3 cubic yards), get a bulk quote from a local landscape supplier. Bagged soil costs 3&ndash;5x more per cubic foot than bulk once you factor in delivery. The calculator above shows your total in <strong>cubic yards</strong> so you can compare both options easily.
    </p>

    <h2 id="worked-example">Worked Example</h2>

    <p>
      Let&rsquo;s walk through a <strong>4&times;8 foot raised bed</strong> filled to <strong>10 inches</strong> deep &mdash; a very common setup.
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Area:</strong> 4 ft &times; 8 ft = <strong>32 square feet</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Convert depth to feet:</strong> 10 inches &divide; 12 = <strong>0.833 feet</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Cubic feet:</strong> 32 sq ft &times; 0.833 ft = <strong>26.7 cubic feet</strong> of soil.</li>
      <li><strong>Cubic yards:</strong> 26.7 &divide; 27 = <strong>~0.99 cubic yards</strong> (round to 1 yard for a bulk order).</li>
      <li><strong>Bags (1.5 cu ft):</strong> 26.7 &divide; 1.5 = 17.8 &rarr; <strong>18 bags</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Bags (2 cu ft):</strong> 26.7 &divide; 2 = 13.35 &rarr; <strong>14 bags</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Estimated weight:</strong> 26.7 cu ft &times; 53.3 lbs/cu ft &asymp; <strong>~1,423 lbs</strong>.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      So for a 4&times;8 bed at 10 inches, you need roughly <strong>26.7 cubic feet</strong>, <strong>1 cubic yard</strong>, or about <strong>18 standard bags</strong> of 1.5 cu ft soil. Add 10&ndash;15% extra to account for settling &mdash; soil always compresses after the first watering.
    </p>

    <LeadMagnet variant="compact" />

    <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common Mistakes</h2>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Not accounting for settling.</strong> Loose bagged soil can settle 10&ndash;20% after the first good rain. Fill slightly past your target depth and let it settle before planting, or plan to top off in spring.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Using straight garden soil.</strong> Native soil pulled from your yard compacts in a raised bed into a dense, poorly draining block. Always use a proper raised bed mix or at minimum blend in compost and perlite.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Ignoring the compost ratio.</strong> Under-composted soil runs out of nutrients fast. At least 25&ndash;30% by volume should be mature compost. More is fine; less means more fertilizing all season.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Underestimating depth.</strong> A 4-inch-deep bed is barely a planter box. For productive vegetable growing, shoot for 10&ndash;12 inches minimum. Shallower beds heat up faster, dry out quicker, and stunt deep-rooted crops.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Filling a bed to its full height when it doesn&rsquo;t need to be.</strong> If your bed sits directly on native soil or grass (not on a patio, deck, or other hard surface), roots aren&rsquo;t stopped by the bottom of the frame &mdash; they can grow on past it into the ground below. Match fill depth to what you&rsquo;re actually growing: shallow crops like lettuce, radishes, and most herbs don&rsquo;t need a bed filled to the brim, even if the frame itself is 12 inches tall. This is one of the easiest ways to cut your soil cost on a large bed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Buying bagged past the bulk threshold.</strong> Once your order exceeds about 2 cubic yards (54 bags), bulk delivery from a landscape yard almost always beats bagged. Get a quote before you load up a cart at the garden center.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <FAQBlock id="raised-bed-soil-calculator-faq" heading="Raised Bed Soil Calculator FAQ" faqs={faqs} />

    <LeadMagnet variant="compact" />

    <h2 id="sources-and-further-reading">Sources &amp; further reading</h2>
    <p>
      Soil depth and mix ratio guidance in this article draws on general recommendations from university cooperative extension services and widely published raised bed gardening resources. For more on how we build and verify the formulas behind every calculator on this site, see our <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>.
    </p>

    <RelatedCalculatorsList id="related-calculators" items={[
      { name: 'Soil & Amendments calculator suite', url: '/clusters/soil-and-amendments/', anchorText: 'Soil & Amendments calculator suite', note: 'our full set of soil, mulch, and compost calculators.' },
      { name: 'Compost Calculator', url: '/calculators/compost-calculator/', note: 'figure out exactly how much compost to mix into your raised bed at the standard 30% ratio.' },
      { name: 'Topsoil Calculator', url: '/calculators/topsoil-calculator/', note: 'compare with our Topsoil Calculator if you\'re buying bulk topsoil by the yard or ton.' },
      { name: 'Soil Volume Calculator', url: '/calculators/soil-volume-calculator/', note: 'for pots and containers, use our Soil Volume Calculator to find the right amount for any pot shape or size.' },
    ]} />

    <p class="mt-12 text-sm text-bark-500">
      Last updated: {formattedDate}.
    </p>
  </article>
</CalculatorLayout>
